{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nNew local shell/session/worktree writes on this machine are **attributed but unsigned**:\nthere is no persistent `[identity] signing_key`, no `REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY`, and no\n`.rebar/current_identity` pointer. The store currently holds **0 signed events out of ~5097\nin-scope events** (`rebar verify-identity --all` reports 0 `verified`) — which agrees with the\ncommitted `rebar.toml` rollout-prep note \"the store currently holds 0 signed events\". (An\nearlier draft said \"~4 demo signed events\"; the measured count is 0, so this Why is corrected\nto match the codebase artifact.) Until every local session signs in steady state, flipping\n`identity.require_authenticated` would reject every local write (bug `27ae-8322-9278-4a7c`).\n\n## Precondition — identity already exists (verified here, NOT created)\n\nThe Rebar Bot **identity ticket already exists** in the store: `594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d`\n(\"Rebar Bot\"), `email = joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com`, with **one registered ed25519 public\nkey** (`ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIHe3p+OG3L79IIh99qRBEkAEXaU+VbeQcSfhIu4M2F8b`).\nThis machine's `git config user.email` is `joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com`, so\n`resolve_current_identity` resolves to 594c by the **git-email fallback**\n(`src/rebar/_commands/identity.py:530-544`, `_match_by_email`) — **no `.rebar/current_identity`\npointer is required** (the pointer only disambiguates when >1 identity shares an email; exactly\none matches here). This story therefore **confirms/probes** the identity and its key; it creates\none only if the probe shows it absent. This machine operates *as* the bot (its git email is the\nbot email), so it legitimately reuses the shared Rebar Bot key rather than minting a separate\nper-clone identity.\n\n## What\n\nProvision a **persistent, machine-wide** signing key so every new shell/session/worktree on\nthis machine signs with no per-session setup:\n\n- **Materialize** the Rebar Bot private key from AWS SSM SecureString\n  `/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key` (ADR-0012) to a `0600` file **outside the repo** at\n  `~/.ssh/rebar-bot-signing-key`. Never commit it; never echo it to logs.\n- **Configure** `[identity] signing_key = \"~/.ssh/rebar-bot-signing-key\"` in the **XDG user\n  config `~/.config/rebar/config.toml`** — the per-machine, git-ignored config the loader\n  merges under `project` precedence (`config.py` `LAYER_ORDER = default,user,project,env,cli`;\n  the project `rebar.toml` sets no `signing_key`, so the user value wins in **every** worktree).\n  This file is the single chosen mechanism — preferred over exporting\n  `REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY` from a shell profile because it is **worktree- and\n  shell-profile-independent**: a fresh non-login shell in any worktree reads it with no\n  re-export. (`.rebar/config.conf` is tombstoned — `src/rebar/_deprecations.py:193` — and must\n  not be used; the shared, committed `rebar.toml` must not carry a per-machine key path.)\n- **Confirm** the public key registered on identity 594c is the public half of the configured\n  private key.\n\n## Scope\n\nThis machine's local clones only. GitHub Actions signing (4dc0) and Gerrit-side signing (1a51)\nare separate stories; the enforcement flip is 8d39. This story changes **no tracked repo\nfiles** — it writes only `~/.config/rebar/config.toml` and `~/.ssh/rebar-bot-signing-key`, both\noutside the repo (hence an empty `file_impact` is correct). The provisioning steps are captured\nin the local runbook (AC5); a shared CLAUDE.md/ADR record of the pattern is deferred to the\nenforcement-flip story.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] **Identity precondition confirmed.** `rebar show 594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d` is an `identity`\n      with the bot email and ≥1 registered key. Proving command:\n      `rebar show 594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d | jq -e '.ticket_type==\"identity\" and (.email|ascii_downcase==\"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com\") and ((.keys|length)>=1)'`\n      exits 0.\n- [ ] **Registered public key equals the configured private key's public half.** Proving\n      command:\n      `diff <(ssh-keygen -y -f ~/.ssh/rebar-bot-signing-key | awk '{print $1,$2}') <(rebar show 594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d | jq -r '.keys[0]' | awk '{print $1,$2}')`\n      exits 0.\n- [ ] **git email matches the identity email.** Proving command:\n      `test \"$(git config user.email)\" = \"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com\"`.\n- [ ] **A fresh worktree signs with no per-session setup.** From a worktree/shell *other* than\n      where the key was configured, `rebar comment <t> \"signing-probe\"` then\n      `rebar show <t> | jq -e '.authorship.signed >= 1'` exits 0, and the new event is\n      `verified`:\n      `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq -e '[.[]|select(.ticket_id==\"<t>\")]|any(.verdict==\"verified\")'`\n      exits 0.\n- [ ] [operator-attested] The private key file is mode `0600`, lives outside the repo at\n      `~/.ssh/rebar-bot-signing-key`, and the setup is captured in the local runbook. Evidence\n      recorded on this ticket as a comment: the `ls -l ~/.ssh/rebar-bot-signing-key` mode line\n      (proving `0600`), the SSM source param (`/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key`), and the\n      identity id (`594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d`)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784234046544466001,"uuid":"5275b22b-ad4c-4cc1-bd6f-9471931dfa30"}